#11

The histograms on the book are bad examples. There should be no gap between the bins.

  • If you think the bins are based on the following intervals [15, 16), [16, 17), [17, 18), [18, 19), [19, 20), [20, 21), [21, 22), [22, 23), [23, 24), [24, 25], then the book answers make sense.

    1. Use the largest possible value on each interval, i.e., 16, 17, , 25. \[\dfrac{16\times 1 + 17\times 3 + 18 \times 3 + 19 \times 4 + 20 \times 6 + 21 \times 4 + 22 \times 3 + 23 \times 5 + 24 \times 2 + 25\times 3}{34} \]
    2. Use the largest possible value on each interval, i.e., 16, 17, , 25.
    3. Use the smallest possible value on each interval, i.e., 15, 16, , 24.
    4. Use the smallest possible value on each interval, i.e., 15, 16, , 24.

  • Otherwise, if you believe the bins are based on the following intervals [14.5, 15.5), [15.5, 16.5), [16.5, 17.5), [17.5, 18.5), [18.5, 19.5), [19.5, 20.5), [20.5, 21.5), [21.5, 22.5), [22.5, 23.5), [23.5, 24.5], then your answers will be

Homework 5

Section 4.5

#11

12/2028 = 0.0059172

The event that two cards are of different suits has \(52\times 39 = 2028\) outcomes. (The first card can be any of the 52 cards. But once the first card is drawn, the second card is limited to one of the oher three suits, i.e., one of 39 cards.)

Of those 2028 outcomes, 12 are corresponding to both cards are aces. (The first card can be any of the four aces, then the second card can be any of the rest three aces.)

Section 5.3

#29

Let \(X\) be the number of cakes sold. If the bakery bakes 2 cakes daily, then the probability distribution of \(X\) is

\(X\) \(P(X)\)
0 0.15
1 0.25
2 0.6
  • If no cake is sold, the profit is \(-4\times 2 = -8\) dollars. (Probability 0.15)
  • If one cake is sold, the profit is \(20 - 4\times 2 = 12\) dollars. (Probability 0.25)
  • If both cakes are sold, the profit is \(20\times 2 - 4 \times 2=32\) dollars. (Probability 0.6)

Therefore, if two cakes are baked daily, the expected profit is \[-8(0.15) + 12(0.25) + 32(0.6)=\$21.\]

Repeat the same process (reconstruct the probability distribution table) to find the expected profit for baking 3 and 4 cakes, separately. (Answer: $23 if 3 cakes are baked daily and $22 if 4 cakes are baked daily).

Homework 7

Section 7.4

#9

Based on the given information, the sample size is \(n=50\), the population mean is \(\mu=0\), and the population standard deviation is \(\sigma=\sqrt{\frac{1}{12}}\). (Note: standard deviation is the square root of variance.) According to the Central Limit Theorem, the sampling distribution of sample means will have a mean of \(\mu = 0\) and a standard deviation of \(\sigma_{\tiny \overline{x}}=\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}=\frac{\sqrt{1/12}}{\sqrt{50}}\).

If the sum of the 50 numbers in the sample differs from the exact sum by 3, then the sample mean \(\overline{x}\) differs by \(3/50=0.06\), meaning \(\overline{x}\) is either larger or smaller than the true sum by 0.06. Therefore,

\(P(|\overline{x}-\mu|>0.06)=P(|\overline{x}|>0.06)=P(\overline{x}>0.06)+P(\overline{x}<-0.06)\)

1 - pnorm(0.06, 0, sqrt(1/12) / sqrt(50)) + pnorm(-0.06, 0, sqrt(1/12) / sqrt(50))
## [1] 0.1416447

Section 9.5

#1

Let \(p\) be the true proportion of patients who get effective treatment by using the new drug.

  • \(H_0: p = 0.72\)
  • \(H_1: p>0.72\)
  • P-value:
1 - pbinom(41, 50, 0.72)
## [1] 0.03645886
1 - pnorm(41.5/50, 0.72, sqrt(0.72 * 0.28 / 50))
## [1] 0.04160677

Conclusion: Based on a 0.05 significance level, the p-value is small. We reject the null hypothesis. There is sufficient evidence to show that the new drug is more effective than the old one.
